The /flow-goal continuation engine fires but doesn't actually execute flows. The defaultSpawn in src/flow-goal/index.ts just calls pi.sendMessage which echoes text without triggering the model to call the flow tool.

Fix these files:

1. src/flow-goal/index.ts — Change the defaultSpawn to use pi.sendUserMessage so the model sees it as a user request and calls the flow tool. Remove the standalone sendMessage call that just echoes text. Make it:

```
const defaultSpawn: SpawnContinuation = async (flows) => {
    const lines = flows.map((f) => `Execute: {"flow": [{"type": "${f.type}", "intent": "${f.intent}", "aim": "${f.aim}"${f.acceptance ? `, "acceptance": "${f.acceptance}"` : ''}}]}`).join('\n');
    pi.sendUserMessage(lines);
};
```

2. src/flow-goal/continuation.ts — Remove the hasFlowTool check (lines 95-98) which uses fragile string matching. Instead, the continuation should ALWAYS attempt to spawn when goal is active and no guard fails. Also remove the standalone sendMessage call for the continuation template — the spawn callback handles everything.

Read both files first, then make the changes. Run npm run build to verify compilation.

The /flow-goal continuation engine sends text messages via pi.sendUserMessage but the model never actually calls the flow tool. Fix by making the continuation engine execute flows DIRECTLY via the executor.

Changes needed:

1. src/flow-goal/types.ts — Change SpawnContinuation type to accept a more generic interface that can carry flow execution context:
```typescript
export type SpawnContinuation = (
  flows: Array<{ type: string; intent: string; aim: string; acceptance?: string }>,
) => Promise<void>;
```
This stays the same — the callback handles everything.

2. src/flow-goal/continuation.ts — After spawning, also call recordFlowCompletion to prevent the continuation from re-firing immediately. The issue is that the spawn callback returns without recording completion, so the guard never triggers.

3. src/flow-goal/index.ts — The REAL fix. Change the defaultSpawn to directly execute flows instead of sending a text message. It needs to:
   a. Accept an executeFlows callback in registerFlowGoal
   b. Default to sending a proper flow tool call message if no callback provided
   c. Record flow completion after execution

Here's the new approach for registerFlowGoal:

```typescript
export type ExecuteFlowsFn = (
  params: Array<{ type: string; intent: string; aim: string; acceptance?: string }>,
) => Promise<Array<{ type: string; intent: string; aim: string; usage: { input: number; output: number } }>>;

export function registerFlowGoal(
  pi: ExtensionAPI,
  opts?: { spawnContinuation?: SpawnContinuation; executeFlows?: ExecuteFlowsFn },
): void {
  // ...
  const spawnFn: SpawnContinuation = opts?.spawnContinuation ?? (async (flows) => {
    if (opts?.executeFlows) {
      const results = await opts.executeFlows(flows);
      for (const r of results) {
        recordFlowCompletion(cwd!, { type: r.type, intent: r.intent, aim: r.aim });
        addTokens(cwd!, r.usage.input + r.usage.output);
      }
    } else {
      // Fallback: send as user message
      const flowJson = JSON.stringify({ flow: flows.map(f => ({ type: f.type, intent: f.intent, aim: f.aim, ...(f.acceptance ? { acceptance: f.acceptance } : {}) })) });
      pi.sendUserMessage(flowJson);
    }
  });
  setupContinuation(pi, () => _currentCwd, spawnFn);
}
```

4. src/index.ts — Pass executeFlows callback to registerFlowGoal. Find where registerFlowGoal is called and add the executeFlows callback:

```typescript
